  "local_port": 37946,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What should I do to get selected in GSOC 2018?",
  "response": "Getting selected for Google Summer of Code (GSoC) is a competitive process, but with proper planning and effort, you can increase your chances of success. Here are the steps you should follow to maximize your chances of being selected for GSoC 2018 (or any other year):\n\n---\n\n### **1. Start Early**\n- **Research the program**: Understand how GSoC works, its timeline, and eligibility criteria.\n- **Check the list of organizations**: Explore the organizations participating in GSoC 2018 and identify ones that align with your skills and interests.\n\n---\n\n### **2. Choose the Right Organization**\n- **Look for a good fit**: Choose organizations that use technologies or programming languages you are familiar with or are eager to learn.\n- **Evaluate complexity**: Some organizations are more competitive than others. Balance your skill level with the organization\u2019s expectations.\n- **Check past projects**: Review previous GSoC projects to understand the type of work involved.\n\n---\n\n### **3. Build Relevant Skills**\n- **Learn required technologies**: If the organization uses specific tools, frameworks, or languages, spend time learning them.\n- **Contribute to open source**: Start contributing to the organization\u2019s open-source projects. Fix bugs, write documentation, or add small features.\n- **Show initiative**: Consistent contributions demonstrate your commitment and help you stand out.\n\n---\n\n### **4. Interact with the Community**\n- **Join communication channels**: Most organizations have mailing lists, chat rooms, or forums. Introduce yourself and ask questions.\n- **Engage with mentors**: Build relationships with potential mentors by discussing ideas and seeking feedback.\n- **Be proactive**: Show enthusiasm and curiosity about the organization\u2019s projects and goals.\n\n---\n\n### **5. Prepare a Strong Proposal**\n- **Research project ideas**: Most organizations provide a list of project ideas. Choose one that excites you and aligns with your skills.\n- **Write a detailed proposal**: Clearly explain your approach, timeline, and deliverables. Include research, design, and implementation details.\n- **Seek feedback**: Share your proposal with mentors and community members and incorporate their suggestions.\n- **Be unique**: Personalize your proposal to reflect your understanding of the project and your passion for it.\n\n---\n\n### **6. Demonstrate Your Skills**\n- **Show prior work**: Include links to your GitHub profile, open-source contributions, or personal projects.\n- **Highlight achievements**: Mention any relevant experience, such as internships, hackathons, or academic projects.\n- **Be honest**: Don\u2019t exaggerate your skills. Mentors appreciate honesty and a willingness to learn.\n\n---\n\n### **7. Stay Organized**\n- **Keep track of deadlines**: Note important dates for GSoC, such as proposal submission and evaluation periods.\n- **Communicate regularly**: Stay in touch with the organization and mentors during the application process.\n- **Backup options**: Apply to multiple organizations or projects to increase your chances.\n\n---\n\n### **8. Prepare for Interviews**\n- **Be ready to explain your proposal**: Mentors may ask questions about your approach or technical details.\n- **Show enthusiasm**: Demonstrate your passion for the project and the organization\u2019s mission.\n- **Practice problem-solving**: Be prepared to solve coding or design challenges during the interview.\n\n---\n\n### **9. Stay Persistent**\n- **Don\u2019t get discouraged**: If you\u2019re not selected, continue contributing to open source and apply again the next year.\n- **Learn from feedback**: Ask mentors for feedback on your proposal or interview to improve for future opportunities.\n\n---\n\n### **10. Final Checklist**\n- Ensure your proposal is error-free and well-structured.\n- Submit your proposal before the deadline.\n- Follow up with the organization if you have questions or updates.\n\n---\n\nBy following these steps, you\u2019ll increase your chances of being selected for GSoC 2018. Remember, GSoC is not just about coding but also about contributing to open source and being part of a community. Good luck!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
